div.div: An insight path is an optimal pattern across systems that's built out of core functions from a general interface filter (type, intent, function, structure) - where interfaces are analogous to indexes/filters.

A basic unit example is 'trial and error' or 'statistical regression' or 'break up the problem into smaller problems & solve them separately, then aggregate solution output' - these are standard abstract rule sets/sequences to apply when discovering new insights in a system, which can be used across systems. You can call these specific strategies, but they can also be considered insight-generators or solution-filters, as they can reduce the solution space when narrowing down possible insights describing a link to the correct linking rule. These examples are not always ideal/efficient so they're not top priority methods, but they're a good example of what position an insight path occupies in a system.

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: An actual useful insight path would solve a common, abstract difficult problem, like 'generating the idea of regression', which would be something like:

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: - query for concept adjacent to balance/equivalence in the context of a data set output (average)

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: - apply the concept of average to indicate a general average distance within output range specified by input format (point subsets) in an input (data set)

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: - find a definition of 'average between output ranges of point subsets' that matches the change type you're aiming for (ie, least squares)

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: - find a definition of the format 'point subsets' that matches your average definition (adjacent points with euclidean distance definition, in subsets of the data set with a particular change rate)

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: - format the input (calculate the data set subsets) using the 'point subsets' definition

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: - apply the definition for 'average between output ranges of point subsets' to the formatted input (calculated data set subsets)

div.style: text-align: left
text-align: left

div.div: This insight path can be used to find a method to solve a problem (a solution) based on an insight discovered during the process (average distance is a good way to determine a regression line). This insight path generates that insight by starting from common useful concepts (power, balance, equal, distance) and applying them to the problem space to find definitions applying those concepts, then using those definitions to convert problem space information to a solution.

div.style: text-align: left
text-align: left

div.div: The idea is to find a reusable method to generate insights. Any set of linking insights/rules between system objects can be an insight path itself, if it applies across systems.

Insight paths don't have to be human-acquired insights - microorganisms often have to find a piece of DNA or functionality using insight paths too, and animals can occasionally solve problems with reliable cross-system methods, although more often we see them use specific insights like 'hit it with a stone and check if it stops moving - if not, it's a plant' (a corresponding insight path there would be 'use adjacent resources to test a differentiating attribute to derive a type'). There are also insight paths implied in useful programming algorithms.

An insight path can be a structure (method of generating an insight path) or content filling a structure (specific insight path involving specific functions/nodes, usually specific to an abstract or other cross-system interface).

For example, it can include a general instruction 'find type & adjust any attribute' or a specific instruction 'find hub node, traverse 3 nodes away in direction of other primary hub, changing direction a maximum of one time during traversal'.
An insight path can trigger insights or generate insights (insights of a particular type or a specific insight.

An insight path is not just a trajectory/trigger/generator of an insight or an insight set, but an efficient path. Any combination of steps could produce an insight, but does a particular path produce insights faster than another path or a random path? If so, it's a candidate for an insight path.

div.div: For example, when teaching the same topic, people will probably have similar instincts on what to include in their explanation.
1. include a visual of the related structures, starting with general objects & links
2. include more detail based on what is relevant
4. realize an important object for understanding is missing and add that, re-formatting as necessary
An insight path would output the necessary objects to include in the explanation, based on insight patterns.
Rather than navigating through all the objects like an amateur (general structure -> details -> filter details -> important details), you can skip from the general structure to the important

The insight path would identify that important concepts are usually hubs between other concepts, because hubs are usually important in other networks (filter is a hub concept for the neural network, so include filters & related objects/concepts)..
The path would also identify that details included should be unique (don't include extra layers in a neural network diagram).
These rules are an example of implementing an abstract path:
To a specific problem space (explanation) and a specific topic (neural networks).
The point of the insight path is to apply insight patterns to skip to expert insights without the learning.

div.div: These are abstract system insight paths, which provide a basis for generative insight paths - functions that involve identifying & applying distortions to key objects in a system to generate insights about system relationships.
These are tools to learn an unknown field quickly - there are many paths between objects that are useful but insight paths point to the key relationships to understand a system's core.
Insight paths can often be mixed across types, creating new insight paths of their functions.

For example, "identify unit or smallest example, then apply common distortions and observe change in properties" is a common insight path across systems that is used to solve problems, but which can also provide insights about systems. The fact that there are core objects & functions is a useful object layer to start with when deconstructing a new system or field.
As a specific example, applying that insight to a new field like quantum physics would yield relationships like:

"unit example of a superposition is a network of possible states, similar to a decision tree - applying the function 'decide trajectory' from the decision tree system to the superposition system indicates a path of superposition collapse. Then you'd apply the concept of a 'pattern' to look for a particular pattern in the path of a superposition collapse to see if you can frame superposition collapse as a decision tree starting from a source node.

This analysis provides a starting point to find insights in new fields - sometimes just applying an insight path is enough to find an insight, rather than an origin to base further distortions on when looking for adjacent insights to the generated insight.

div.div: How would you pick a route to the coast, knowing nothing about the terrain except what you can see ahead?
You can start by theorizing the existence of objects created by extreme/intersecting/compounding attributes:
- an angle taken to its extreme would cause a 'cliff' object
- another angle with equivalent increase & decrease would cause a 'hill' object
- an opposite pattern of the 'hill' object would be a 'crevice' object
How can you check for these objects to help select a route?
- check the route you took to get at your current location, applying the insight that 'patterns often repeat', to gauge the slope of the hill

- check for signals of sub-objects (hill, cliff) by the signals that those sub-objects would leave (tops of trees of decreasing height visible before the horizon of land, beyond which you can't tell what the terrain is like before the coast
- theorize the existence of a 'port' and check for signals of that object, like boats that are aiming at a particular location if the sea is visible

This is an example of the insight paths 'use extreme/intersecting/compound attributes as probable sources of objects developing in a space' and 'theorize objects or sub-systems in an unknown territory and check for signals they would produce' applied to the 'predict terrain' problem space in the unknown 'terrain' system - another path would be 'theorize object interactions and check for signals of that interaction', or 'theorize attribute accretion and check for signals of an object'.

div.div:
Abstracting the insight path allows you to store a pattern for the insight path - and adjusting the insight path after identifying its variables is a way to apply the insight path in the same problem space/system context.
You can apply other interfaces than the abstract interface (standardizing to the intent interface, the type interface, the function interface, etc
You can also inject prior information to the insight path, so it's making different connections.
For example, instead of just identifying an object by its type that was known at the insight development time (bacteria), you can apply knowledge about the object's metadata, to form a different insight path - one that builds on the bacteria's known attributes rather than an insight path built on just its type identifier. Rather than calling it bacteria, you can call it a competitor since the virus can act as a competitor to the bacteria in some contexts, or you can call it an information-processing unit, a testing tool, a stressor, a change interface, or whatever standardized format the object can take that is most useful for highlighting differences between objects or building a useful cross-system insight path.
Once you abstract an insight path or standardize it to another cross-system interface, it can be applied to generate insights in a new field.

At the inner layer is the base for distortion. The next layer is the core distortion functions.
The next layer is the base layer (set of common bases.
The next layer is the key number layer, including a number of each important type (important constants for calculation,
bases, illustration of number types (irrational number 2 ^ 1/2, number needed to determine fibonacci sequence, prime number, etc).

The outer layer is the ratio layer, where numbers are inefficient to represent as themselves and are more efficient to represent as relations between other numbers (irrational numbers as vacillations around a center, infinities as a ratio to other infinities, limits as a convergence of a sum).
Framing numbers in this way can reveal insights about the description system.

Insight Paths as an Optimization Tool
This isn't just a derivation/discovery system - it can be applied to optimize a system once the full or partial causal stack of a phenomenon is determined.
For example, stretching the system to make it allow only a line of objects rather than a cluster of objects would invalidate the emergent rotation operation, and would prevent square from converting into circles through repeated rotations.
So if your goal is to optimize the system to prevent circles from developing, applying the 'stretch' transform to the system is one way to prevent that, if it doesn't invalidate other functionality.
A normal solution without system analysis would be: "inject something that can kill the circles" - which doesn't take into account the root cause and doesn't prevent the problem from developing again - it's just a reactionary approach that doesn't fix the problem, only its side effects & in a way that needs to be repeated to work. This type of solution can be optimal in a system that needs to be adaptable so that repeated solution applications are a good approach, because they can be stopped once other solutions are applied or if the circles start being necessary, but given the alternative solutions, it's not likely to be optimal in this system.
Isolating the functionality with a boundary so it's only accessible with certain proofs of intent
is another way to optimize the system.

div.div: Trajectories between core system objects/functions and the important system objects/functions follow network patterns because the important objects are those which:
- are highly connected with other nodes
- have generative capacity (functions that can generate other functions on the same layer or another layer)
- are adjacent to or already in a standard format which all other objects can be transformed to
- occupy an interim interface/interaction layer/sub-system between other interfaces/interaction layers/sub-systems

- occupy a high-causation node on the causal interface, such as a root causal node of the system, a hub node, a causal-structure-generating node (a node that creates causal loops/connections between other nodes)
- are abstract & could be causal nodes across systems
- are self-generating, self-correcting, self-regulating or re-generate the system in a stable low-cost efficient state

Impact Variation of Similar/Equal Attributes
Why would shapes with similar or equivalent structure have different impact in a system?
Several common reasons include:
- change of system position (the shape position is changed) orientation (the shape is flipped or transformed about a symmetry)
- change of dimension (a dimension is added, for example changing a 2-d structure into a 3-d structure by making it non-flat)
- interaction potential (one shape can interact with other shapes that can use an attribute/function of the shape, whereas the other shape doesn't have access to that shape community)
- flexibility potential (one shape is more flexible than the other, despite their similar structure at a given time)
- change patterns (the similarity was transient - one shape was only that shape for a brief period of time during a measured transition, whereas the other shape regularly collapses back to that shape bc it's a fundamental identity of that shape)
- measurability (we can only measure the attributes that seem or are similar across the shapes)
- the similarity was illusory (the similarity appeared to exist but it was a fault of the measurement which only captured one state or a subset of determining attributes or involved a transform like a scale change that made them appear similar)
